or 1 needs Integration level—mock the GitHub PR API to return a diff and verify the agent receives only changed lines. Behavior 2 requires System level—create an actual GitHub PR and confirm inline comments land at the correct positions in the UI. Behavior 3 needs System level to validate real GitHub API responses. Behavior 4 requires Agentic testing since it depends on actual LLM output format. Behavior 5 needs Workflow level for the full end-to-end sequence with real GitHub and real LLM. verify that the summary comment appears after all inline comments are posted. This tests the complete orchestration and timing of the system.\n\nFor behavior 3, the agent needs to identify real defects in actual code. I'm calling the real LLM API with a PR containing a known bug—like a missing null check or race condition—and checking that the agent catches it. Since LLM outputs vary, I'll run this multiple times to account for that variability. Mocking the model would only test the mock itself, not whether the system actually works.\n\nBehavior 4 focuses on consistency between the summary and inline comments. I'll mock GitHub's API, run the agent on a test PR, and capture all POST requests. Then I'll extract findings from the summary comment and verify each one has a matching inline comment posted—no orphaned findings allowed.\n\nFor behavior 5, the entire workflow needs to execute correctly end-to-end. This requires a real GitHub PR and real LLM calls. The test validates that the agent reads the diff, analyzes it for bugs, posts inline comments for each finding, and finally posts the summary comment in the right order.\n\nReconsidering behavior 2: the failure mode is posting an inline comment to the wrong line. A unit test can't catch this because it doesn't understand GitHub's API semantics. An integration test with a sophisticated mock might catch it if the mock validates position numbering, but GitHub's position logic is complex. Most teams would test this at the system level